SIMPLE: subdue
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subdue
<hw>Sub*due"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Subdued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Subduing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>soduen</ets>, OF.
<ets>sosduire</ets> to seduce, L. <ets>subtus</ets> below (fr.
<ets>sub</ets> under) + <ets>ducere</ets> to lead. See <er>Duke</er>,
and cf. <er>Subduct</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring under; to
conquer by force or the exertion of superior power, and bring into
permanent subjection; to reduce under dominion; to vanquish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>subdue</qex> all thine enemies.</q> <rj><qau>1 Chron.
xvii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To overpower so as to disable from further
resistance; to crush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing could have <qex>subdued</qex> nature⟦br⟧
To such a lowness, but his unkind daughters.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If aught . . . were worthy to <qex>subdue</qex>⟦br⟧
The soul of man.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To destroy the force of; to overcome; <as>as,
medicines <ex>subdue</ex> a fever</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To render submissive; to bring under command; to
reduce to mildness or obedience; to tame; <as>as, to <ex>subdue</ex> a
stubborn child; to <ex>subdue</ex> the temper or
passions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To overcome, as by persuasion or other mild means;
<as>as, to <ex>subdue</ex> opposition by argument or
entreaties</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To reduce to tenderness; to melt; to soften; <as>as,
to <ex>subdue</ex> ferocity by tears</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To make mellow; to break, as land; also, to destroy,
as weeds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To reduce the intensity or degree of; to tone down;
to soften; <as>as, to <ex>subdue</ex> the brilliancy of
colors</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To conquer; overpower; overcome; surmount;
vanquish. See <er>Conquer</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subdued</ent>⟦br⟧
